ramatic clash came in the mid-1980s when late Socialist Premier Andreas Papandreou tried to expropriate the Church's vast land holdings. Seraphim eventually won the battle and in retaliation [[Excommunicate#Eastern Orthodox churches|excommunicated]] seven government officials.\"<ref>Stephen McGregor. ''\"Archbishop Seraphim\".'' The Herald (Glasgow). 11 April 1998. p.19.</ref>|group=note}} on [[August 19 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)|August 19]] Patr. [[Patriarch Pimen I of Moscow|Pimen of Moscow and All Russia]], and Ec. Patr. [[Patriarch Demetrios I of Constantinople|Demetrios I of Constantinople]] co-celebrated the [[Divine Liturgy]] on the [[Feast of the Transfiguration]] at the [[Trinity Lavra of St. Sergius|Holy Trinity St. Sergius Monastery]], being the '''first concelebration in 398 years (since January 1589)'''.<ref>John Garrard and Carol Garrard. ''Russian Orthodoxy Resurgent: Faith and Power in the New Russia.'' Princeton University Press, 2008. p. 1.</ref>\n*1988 Canonization of [[Eustathius of Thessalonica]] (\u20201197);<ref>Great Synaxaristes: {{in lang|el}} ''[http://synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/697/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u1f49 \u1f0d\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u0395\u1f50\u03c3\u03c4\u03ac\u03b8\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f41 \u039a\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac\u03c6\u03bb\u03c9\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f08\u03c1\u03c7\u03b9\u03b5\u03c0\u03af\u03c3\u03ba\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2 \u0398\u03b5\u03c3\u03c3\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2].'' 20 \u03a3\u03b5\u03c0\u03c4\u03b5\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref> Mount Athos<ref>''[https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/454 Mount Athos].'' \u00a9 UNESCO World Heritage Centre 1992\u20132012.</ref> and the [[Meteora]]<ref>''[https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/455 Meteora].'' \u00a9 UNESCO World Heritage Centre 1992\u20132012.</ref> are designated as [[List of World Heritage Sites in Europe#Greece (17)|UNESCO World Heritage sites]]; radio station \"[[List of radio stations in Greece|Church of Piraeus 91.2 FM]]\" begins transmitting in October, through the efforts of Metr. [[:el:\u039a\u03b1\u03bb\u03bb\u03af\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 (\u039a\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03c3\u03bf\u03c2)|Kallinikos (Karousos)]] of Piraeus (1978-2006);<ref>{{in lang|el}} ''[http://www.pe912fm.com/ \u03a1\u0391\u0394\u0399\u039f\u03a6\u03a9\u039d\u0399\u039a\u039f\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a4\u0391\u0398\u039c\u039f\u03a3 \u03a0\u0395\u0399\u03a1\u0391\u03aa\u039a\u0397 \u0395\u039a\u039a\u039b\u0397\u03a3\u0399\u0391].'' Retrieved: 24 July 2013.</ref> death of Fr [[:el:\u0393\u03b5\u03ce\u03c1\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a0\u03c5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2|George Pirounakis]], a turbulent cleric who opposed the right-wing dictatorship of 1967-1974, supported student uprisings against the junta, and later demanded that bishops who had succoured the tyrants should be held to account.<ref>''[https://www.economist.com/blogs/erasmus/2014/11/church-and-state-greece Church and state in Greece: A new concordat?]'' The Economist: Erasmus - Religion and Public Policy. 21 November 2014, 14:48 BY B.C.</ref>\n*1989 Hellenic Bible Society publishes a [[Bible translations into Greek|translation of the New Testament]] into the modern vernacular ([[Demotic Greek]]), '''The New Testament diglot''', containing both the Patriarchal edition of 1904, along with a parallel translation in Today's Greek Version, having the blessing, approval and endorsements of the [[Ecumenical Patriarchate of Constantinople]], the Holy Synod of the [[Church of Greece]], the [[Greek Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Patriarchate of Alexandria]], the [[Greek Orthodox Patriarch of Jerusalem|Patriarchate of Jerusalem]], and the Pedagogical Institute of the [[Ministry of Education, Research and Religious Affairs|Greek Ministry for Education and Religion]];<ref>{{in lang|el}} ''' ''[http://www.greekbibles.org/index.php?id_product=21&controller=product&id_lang=1 \u0397 \u039a\u0391\u0399\u039d\u0397 \u0394\u0399\u0391\u0398\u0397\u039a\u0397: \u03a4\u03bf \u03c0\u03c1\u03c9\u03c4\u03cc\u03c4\u03c5\u03c0\u03bf \u03ba\u03b5\u03af\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03bf \u03bc\u03b5 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03ac\u03c6\u03c1\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7 \u03b4\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae].'' \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u0392\u03b9\u03b2\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u0395\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03af\u03b1, \u0391\u03b8\u03ae\u03bd\u03b1. {{ISBN|9789607847171}}'''</ref> [[Mystras]] is designated as a [[List of World Heritage Sites in Europe#Greece (17)|UNESCO World Heritage site]];<ref>''[https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/511 Archaeological Site of Mystras].'' \u00a9 UNESCO World Heritage Centre 1992\u20132012.</ref>\n*1990 '''Bilateral declarations of both [[Greece\u2013Israel relations|Greece and Israel]]''' are made on 21 May 1990 in which they normalized their diplomatic relations, essentially '''recognizing the special interest of the [[Greek Government]] in a [[Greek Orthodox]] presence in the [[Holy places#Christianity|Holy Places]]''', as well as its right to have a say in any future arrangements concerning the religious status quo and the rights and privileges of the [[Greek Orthodox Church of Jerusalem|Patriarchate of Jerusalem]];<ref>Sotiris Roussos. ''THE PATRIARCHATE OF JERUSALEM IN THE GREEK-PALESTINIAN-ISRAELI TRIANGLE: IS THERE A PLACE FOR IT?'' Athens, 1 March 2003. p. 8.</ref> the monasteries of [[Daphni Monastery|Daphni]] (Athens), [[Hosios Loukas]] (Beotia) and [[Nea Moni of Chios]], are designated as [[List of World Heritage Sites in Europe#Greece (17)|UNESCO World Heritage sites]];<ref>''[https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/537 Monasteries of Daphni, Hosios Loukas and Nea Moni of Chios].'' \u00a9 UNESCO World Heritage Centre 1992\u20132012.</ref> death of Fr. Athanasios Anthides, first Greek Orthodox Missionary to India, succeeded a year later by [[Hieromonk|priest-monk]] Fr. Ignatios Sennis, who came to [[Kolkata|Calcutta]] to continue the mission;<ref name=ORIANTHIDES/> the [[Mount Athos#The Friends of Mount Athos|Friends of Mount Athos]] society is formed, with Metr. [[Timothy Ware|Kallistos (Ware)]] of Diokleia as President,<ref>''[http://www.athosfriends.org/ Friends of Mount Athos Online].'' '''The Friends of Mount Athos'''. Retrieved: 24 July 2013.</ref> including [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]] (Duke of Edinburgh) and [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]] (The Prince of Wales) among its members.<ref>''[http://www.athosfriends.org/about/officiary/ The Officiary of the Friends of Mount Athos].'' '''The Friends of Mount Athos'''. Retrieved: 24 July 2013.</ref>\n*1991 Death of Elder [[Porphyrios Bairaktaris|Porphyrios (Bairaktaris) the Kapsokalivite]] (Evangelos (Bairaktaris)) 7 February;<ref>Kleitos I\u014dannid\u0113s, and Charles J. Simones. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=7FYnAAAACAAJ&dq=Porphyrios+testimonies+and+experiences&source=bl&ots=0TY8AXm_Ve&sig=zBcVw_NHmjcvIVfUfpQlXmqJlw8&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Jr9UUNy1EKrE0AH4-YGIBw&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA Elder Porphyrios testimonies and experiences].'' Holy Convent of the Transfiguration of the Savior, 1997. 367 pp. {{ISBN|9789608538238}}</ref><ref>''[http://www.orthodoxphotos.com/Orthodox_Elders/Greek/Fr._Porphyrios/ A Short Biography of Elder Porphyrios the Kapsokalivite].'' OrthodoxPhotos.com.</ref> '''[[orthodoxwiki:Kyriopascha|Kyriopascha]] occurs''';<ref group=\"note\" name=\"Kyriopascha\">From antiquity the Orthodox Church has celebrated with special liturgical joy the occurrence when [[Easter|Pascha]] falls on [[March 25 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)|25 March]] ([[Julian calendar|Old Style]]) - the [[Feast of the Annunciation]], calling it ''\"Kyriopascha,\"'' \"the Lord's Pascha\". It was precisely on the coincidence of the Feasts of the Annunciation and Pascha on 25 March 1821 (Old Style), that Greece challenged the Turkish Yoke. Kyriopascha has also manifested its miraculous Grace to our own generation by its most recent occurrence in 1991, the year of the demise of Communism in Russia, a demise which, furthermore, was finalized by a last, desperate gasp in the form of an abortive Communist coup thwarted on 6 August (Old Style)\u2013the Feast of the Transfiguration. The last Kyriopascha on the Julian calendar was in 1991; the next will be in 2075, 2086 and 2159. The last Kyriopascha on the Gregorian Calendar was in 1951, and the next will be in 2035, 2046 and 2103.</ref> '''[[Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of Italy]]''' is created;<ref>''[http://win.ortodossia.it/The%20Holy%20Orthodox%20Archdiocese%20of%20Italy%20ed%20Malta.htm The Holy Orthodox Archdiocese of Italy and Malta].'' Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of Italy. Retrieved: 29 July 2014.</ref> '''[[Syncretism|syncretistic]] synod of the [[Greek Orthodox Church of Antioch|Antiochian Patriarchate]]''' convened and presided over by Patriarch [[Ignatius IV of Antioch]], and attended by the heretical [[Monophysitism|Monophysite]] Jacobite Syrian Patriarch [[Ignatius Zakka I Iwas|Ignatius Zakka]], implements a series of measures aimed at achieving full union with the Monophysite [[Syriac Christianity|Syriac Churches]], declaring their patriarchates to be \"sister churches\"<ref name=1991-SYRIAC-ANTIOCH-STMT>''[http://sor.cua.edu/Ecumenism/19911112socrumorthstmt.html Statement of the Orthodox Church of Antioch on the Relations between the Eastern and Syrian Orthodox Churches].'' '''Syriac Orthodox Resources (SOR)'''. 12 November 1991. Retrieved: 20 August 2016.</ref> despite the [[Christology|Christological]] differences, and allowing joint prayer in the agreed statement.<ref name=1991-SYRIAC-ANTIOCH-STMT/><ref>''[http://www.gocamerica.org/history_canonicity_text_timeline.shtml Timeline of the Church of the Genuine Orthodox Christians of Russia and Greece and the Great Apostasy of Orthodoxy in the 20th Century].'' TWENTY-FOURTH EDITION. '''Dormition Skete''', Buena Vista, Colorado, U.S.A. MARCH 21, 2016.</ref><ref>''[http://genuineorthodoxchurch.com/A_Time_Line_of_the_20th_and_21st_Centuries.htm Genuine Orthodox Church of the 20th and 21st Centuries: A Time Line].'' '''Genuine Orthodox Church of Greece'''. Retrieved: 20 August 2016.</ref>{{#tag:ref|This action by the Patriarchate of Antioch was protested by the Sacred Community of Mount Athos, in a Letter to the Ecumenical Patriarch Concerning the Balamand Agreement, 8 December 1993, which was signed by all the Representatives and Presidents of the Twenty Sacred Monasteries of the Holy Mountain of Athos:\n:* \"...we cite the case of the Patriarchate of Antioch, which, without a Pan-Orthodox decision, has proceeded to ecclesiastical communion with the Non-Chalcedonians [Monophysites]. This was done despite the fact that a most serious issue has not yet been resolved. It is the latter's non-acceptance of the Ecumenical Councils after the Third and, in particular, the Fourth, the Council of Chalcedon, which in fact constitutes an immovable basis of Orthodoxy. Unfortunately, in this case, too, we have not seen a single protest by other Orthodox Churches.\"<ref name=ATHOS-DEC1993>''[http://orthodoxinfo.com/ecumenism/athos_bal.aspx Letter to the Ecumenical Patriarch Concerning the Balamand Agreement].'' '''Orthodox Christian Information Center'''. Retrieved: 20 August 2016. (From: ''Orthodox Life'', Vol. 44, No. 4, July\u2013August 1994, pp. 26-39.)</ref>|group=note}}\n\n{{multiple image\n| footer = Among the victims of the atrocities committed by the Turkish nationalist Army (1922\u201323) were hundreds of Christian clergy in Anatolia, such as metropolitan bishops (from left): [[Chrysostomos of Smyrna]] (lynched), [[Prokopios Lazaridis|Prokopios of Iconium]] (imprisoned and poisoned) [[Gregory Orologas|Gregory]] of Kydonies (executed), [[Ambrosios Pleianthidis|Ambrosios]] of Moschonisia (buried alive). These bishops were glorified by the Orthodox [[Church of Greece]] in 1992.\n| image1 = Chrysostomos of Smyrna.jpg | width1 = 100 | alt1 = Chrysostomos of Smyrna\n| image2 =| width2 = 106 | alt2 = Prokopios of Iconium\n| image3 = Gregory Orologas of Kydonies.jpg | width3 = 87 | alt3 = Gregory Orologas of Kynonies\n| image4 = Ambrosios of Moschonisia Asia Minor.jpg | width4 = 105 | alt4 = Ambrosios of Moschonisia, Asia Minor}}\n*1992 '''Synaxis of primates of Orthodox churches in Constantinople''';<ref name=GUARDIANHELENASMITH>Helena Smith. ''ORTHODOX LEADERS ACCUSE VATICAN OF STEALING THEIR CHRISTIAN FLOCK.'' '''The Guardian (London)'''. 17 March 1992. Pg. 4.</ref>{{#tag:ref|\"AN unprecedented summit of world Orthodox leaders has ended with a strong attack on the Vatican, harming chances of an early improvement in the deeply troubled relations between the two Christian Church groups. Closing their meeting in Istanbul, the 12 spiritual heads of Eastern Christianity said attempts by Roman Catholics to proselytise in eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union had inflicted a \"most severe wound on the dialogue between the Churches which will be difficult to heal\". The leaders said: \"Traditional Orthodox countries have been considered 'missionary territories' [by the Vatican] and proselytism is practised with all the methods that have been condemned and rejected for decades by all Christians\".\"<ref name=GUARDIANHELENASMITH/>|group=note}} Patr. [[Patriarch Diodoros of Jerusalem|Diodoros I of Jerusalem]] presented a list of '''[http://orthodoxinfo.com/ecumenism/diodoros.aspx firm declarations of Orthodox convictions]''' of the Patriarchate of Jerusalem, which was entered into the minutes of the assembly of Orthodox leaders at the Phanar on the Sunday of Orthodoxy;<ref>[http://orthodoxinfo.com/ecumenism/diodoros.aspx Firm Declarations of Patriarch Diodoros That Strengthen the Faith of Orthodox People]. Orthodox Christian Information Center. Retrieved: 29 July 2014.</ref><ref>Constantine Cavarnos. ''[http://ctosonline.org/ecumenism/QU.html The Question of Union].'' Etna, CA: The Center for Traditionalist Orthodox Studies, 1992 [1964].</ref> on 4 November 1992, the [[Holy Synod]] of the Church of Greece unanimously declared Bp. [[Chrysostomos of Smyrna]] (\u20201922) an Ethnomartyr and a [[Saint]] of the [[Orthodox Church]], to be jointly commemorated on the Sunday before the Feast of the [[Elevation of the Holy Cross]], together with four other Holy Hierarchs of [[Asia Minor]] including: Bp. [[Ambrosios Pleianthidis|Ambrosios Moschonision]], Bp. [[orthodoxwiki:Euthymios (Agritellis) of Zela|Euthymios (Agritellis) of Zela]] (\u20201921), Bp. [[Gregory (Orologas) of Kydonies|Gregorios of Kidonion]] (\u20201922), and Bp. [[Prokopios Lazaridis|Prokopios of Iconium]] (\u20201923);<ref>{{in lang|el}} ''[http://www.triglia.gr/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=26&Itemid=39+%CE%91%CE%B3%CE%B9%CE%BF%CF%82+%CE%A7%CF%81%CF%85%CF%83%CE%BF%CF%83%CF%84%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BF%CF%82+%CE%A3%CE%BC%CE%B7%CF%81%CE%BD%CE%B7%CF%82&ct=clnk \u0391\u03b3. \u03a7\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03cc\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a3\u03bc\u03cd\u03c1\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20110721083437/http://www.triglia.gr/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=26&Itemid=39+%CE%91%CE%B3%CE%B9%CE%BF%CF%82+%CE%A7%CF%81%CF%85%CF%83%CE%BF%CF%83%CF%84%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BF%CF%82+%CE%A3%CE%BC%CE%B7%CF%81%CE%BD%CE%B7%CF%82&ct=clnk |date=21 July 2011 }}.'' Municipality of [[Triglia]]. Retrieved: 7 September 2012.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Their ranking to the chorus of the Saints was formally announced in ''Encyclical 2556, of 5 July 1993, of the Holy Synod of the Church of Greece'' ({{in lang|el}} \u0395\u03b3\u03ba\u03cd\u03ba\u03bb\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 2556 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 5\u03b7\u03c2 \u0399\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 1993 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0399\u03b5\u03c1\u03ac\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c5\u03bd\u03cc\u03b4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0395\u03ba\u03ba\u03bb\u03b7\u03c3\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03bf\u03c2).<ref>{{in lang|el}} \u039a\u03c9\u03bd/\u03c4\u03af\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2 \u0392. \u03a7\u03b9\u03ce\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2. ''\"[http://www.serrelib.gr/arthra.php?id=25 \u039f \u03bc\u03b1\u03c1\u03c4\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03b8\u03ac\u03bd\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u039c\u03b7\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03af\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a3\u03bc\u03cd\u03c1\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2]\"''. \u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1 \u039a\u03b5\u03bd\u03c4\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03b7 \u0392\u03b9\u03b2\u03bb\u03b9\u03bf\u03b8\u03b7\u03ba\u03b7 \u03a3\u03b5\u03c1\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd. \u03a4\u03b5\u03c4\u03ac\u03c1\u03c4\u03b7, 13 \u03a3\u03b5\u03c0\u03c4\u03b5\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 2006.</ref>|group=note}} in June, Patr. [[Alexy II of Moscow]] visits Church of Greece;<ref>''[http://dogma.gr/default.php?pname=Article&art_id=2618&catid=3 \u0388\u03c4\u03c3\u03b9 \u03c5\u03c0\u03bf\u03b4\u03ad\u03c7\u03b8\u03b7\u03ba\u03b5 \u03b7 \u0391\u03b8\u03ae\u03bd\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03a0\u03b1\u03c4\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac\u03c1\u03c7\u03b7 \u0391\u03bb\u03ad\u03be\u03b9\u03bf \u03c0\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc 21 \u03c7\u03c1\u03cc\u03bd\u03b9\u03b1 (\u03a6\u03a9\u03a4\u039f)].'' '''\u0394\u039f\u0393\u039c\u0391: \u03a0\u03a1\u0391\u039a\u03a4\u039f\u03a1\u0395\u0399\u039f \u0395\u039a\u039a\u039b\u0397\u03a3\u0399\u0391\u03a3\u03a4\u0399\u039a\u03a9\u039d \u0395\u0399\u0394\u0397\u03a3\u0395\u03a9\u039d'''. 30 \u039c\u03b1\u03ca\u03bf\u03c5, 2013 | 00:48.</ref> deaths of [[Gerontissa Gavrielia|Eldress Gabrielia]] (Papayannis)<ref>''[http://sgpm.goarch.org/Monastery/?p=14 Gerontissa Gavrielia].'' '''aint Gregory Palamas Greek Orthodox Monastery (Perrysville, OH)'''. Retrieved: 24 July 2013.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Born in Constantinople 2/15 October 1897. Passed from this world on 28 March 1992. Spiritual daughter to Fr. Amphilochios Makris the Elder.|group=note}} and Chrysanthi of Andros;<ref>Mother Nectaria McLees. ''Righteous Chrysanthi of Andros (+ 1992).'' Evlogeite, A Pilgrim's Guide to Greece. St. Nicholas Press, Kansas City, MO, 2002. pp. 96-100.</ref> the total congregation of the [[Greek Orthodox Church of Jerusalem|Patriarchate of Jerusalem]] in 1992 was estimated at 145,000 Greek Orthodox Palestinians in the [[Israeli-occupied territories|Occupied Territories]], [[Israel]] and [[Jordan]], representing the largest Christian congregation in historic Palestine, and Jerusalem in particular.<ref>Sotiris Roussos. ''THE PATRIARCHATE OF JERUSALEM IN THE GREEK-PALESTINIAN-ISRAELI TRIANGLE: IS THERE A PLACE FOR IT?'' Athens, 1 March 2003. pp. 3, 13.</ref>\n*1993 [[Cypriot Orthodox Church|Church of Cyprus]] condemned Freemasonry as a religion incompatible with Christianity;<ref>{{in lang|el}} \u039c\u03b9\u03c7\u03b1\u03ae\u03bb \u039c. ''\u0397 \u03a3\u03c5\u03bd\u03c9\u03bc\u03bf\u03c3\u03af\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u039a\u03cd\u03c0\u03c1\u03bf. \u03a3\u03b9\u03c9\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2-\u039c\u03b1\u03c3\u03bf\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2.'' \u039a\u03cd\u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 1993. \u0392\u0384\u0388\u03ba\u03b4\u03bf\u03c3\u03b7 2003.</ref> [[Joint International Commission for Theological Dialogue Between the Catholic Church and the Orthodox Church|Orthodox-Roman Catholic Joint Theological Commission]] meets in Balamand, Lebanon, issuing common document ''\"Uniatism: Method of Union of the Past, and Present. Search for Full Communion\"'' (the '''\"[[Balamand declaration]]\"'''),<ref>''\"[https://www.vatican.va/roman_curia/pontifical_councils/chrstuni/ch_orthodox_docs/rc_pc_chrstuni_doc_19930624_lebanon_en.html TEXT: UNIATISM, METHOD OF UNION OF THE PAST, AND THE PRESENT SEARCH FOR FULL COMMUNION]\".'' JOINT INTERNATIONAL COMMISSION FOR THE THEOLOGICAL DIALOGUE BETWEEN THE ROMAN CATHOLIC CHURCH AND THE ORTHODOX CHURCH: SEVENTH PLENARY SESSION. Balamand school of theology (Lebanon) 17\u201324 June 1993.</ref> equating the Orthodox and Roman Catholics as \"sister churches\", and concluding that [[rebaptism]] should be avoided, while \"'uniatism' can no longer be accepted either as a method to be followed nor as a model of the unity our Churches are seeking\".{{#tag:ref|This declaration was roundly criticized in Orthodox literature:\n:* ''[http://orthodoxinfo.com/ecumenism/balamand.pdf THE BALAMAND UNION: A Victory of Vatican Diplomacy].'' '''CENTER FOR TRADITIONALIST ORTHODOX STUDIES''', St. Gregory Palamas Monastery, Etna, CA. July\u2013September, 1993. (pdf)\n:* ''[http://orthodoxinfo.com/ecumenism/paphagfr.pdf Papism, the Hagiorite Fathers, and the Aftermath of the \"Balamand Union\"].'' Transl. from the Greek by Patrick G. Barker. '''Hagios Kyprianos''', no. 258 (January\u2013February 1994), pp. 211-215. (pdf)\n:* ''[http://orthodoxinfo.com/ecumenism/athos_bal.aspx Letter to the Ecumenical Patriarch Concerning the Balamand Agreement].'' '''Orthodox Christian Information Center'''. Retrieved: 20 August 2016. (From: ''Orthodox Life'', Vol. 44, No. 4, July\u2013August 1994, pp. 26-39).|group=note}}\n\n*1994 Death of Elder '''[[Elder Paisios|Paisios (Eznepidis)]] of Mt. Athos''', 12 July;<ref>Herman A. Middleton. ''[http://www.orthodoxinfo.com/praxis/preciousvessels.aspx Precious Vessels of the Holy Spirit: The Lives & Counsels of Contemporary Elders of Greece].'' 2nd Ed. Protecting Veil Press, 2004. pp.124\u2013143.</ref> Greek Parliament passes a resolution marking 19 May as \"[[Greek genocide|Pontus Genocide]] Remembrance Day\";<ref>''Pontus genocide monument overshadows relations between Turkey and Greece: Turkish FM.'' '''Xinhua General News Service'''. 12 May 2006 Friday 8:30 AM EST.</ref> the Liaison Office of the Orthodox Church to the European Union was established in Brussels by the [[Ecumenical Patriarchate of Constantinople#The Holy and Sacred Synod|Holy Synod of the Ecumenical Patriarchate]];<ref name=LUCIANLEUSTEAN>Lucian N. Leustean. ''\"Table 1.2 Other Christian Bodies in dialogue with European institutions\".'' I