399\u0391\u039d\u039f\u03a5\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u039f\u03a3-\u03a6\u0395\u0392\u03a1\u039f\u03a5\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u039f\u03a3 2013. p. 6. Retrieved: 3 August 2015.</ref>{{#tag:ref|On Sunday 21 October 2012 the Pope and Patriarch of Alexandria and All Africa, [[Patriarch Theodore II of Alexandria|Theodoros II]], consecrated the '''Church of Saint Andrew in Kananga, Congo''', being the largest Orthodox Church in Africa to date. During his homily, His Beatitude spoke about the vision of the late missionary Fr. '''Charitonas Pneumatikakis''', about the construction of a large Orthodox Church in the region of [[Kananga]], a project which began in 2004 and was completed in 2010 by the then Metropolitan of Central Africa and the current Metropolitan of Pentapoleos, Ignatios.<ref>Fr. John A. Peck. ''[http://journeytoorthodoxy.com/2012/10/largest-orthodox-church-in-africa-consecrated/ Largest Orthodox Church in Africa Consecrated].'' 22 October 2012. Retrieved 8 February 2018.</ref>|group=note}} by an overwhelming parliamentary majority, including both major parties (PASOK and ND), the separation of church and state was excluded (in 1998) from the constitutional revision that was eventually completed in April 2001;<ref name=GM/> [http://www.orthodoxinfo.com/ecumenism/thessaloniki_roc.aspx Thessaloniki Summit] held to discuss Orthodox participation in [[World Council of Churches|WCC]];<ref>''[http://orthodoxinfo.com/ecumenism/thessaloniki_roc.aspx The Thessaloniki Summit May 1998].'' Orthodox Christian Information Center. (''Vestnik'' (No. 3, 1998)). Retrieved: 19 July 2013.</ref> on 8 December the [http://www.bioethics.org.gr/en/03_frame.html Bioethics Committee of the Church of Greece] was created to study contemporary [[Bioethics#Christian bioethics|bioethical problems]] in depth from a scientific viewpoint based on Orthodox ethos and the theological perception of man, society and values;<ref>Hellenic Center for Biomedical Ethics (HCBE). ''[http://www.bioethics.org.gr/en/03_frame.html THE HOLY SYNOD OF THE CHURCH OF GREECE: BIOETHICS COMMITTEE].'' Retrieved: 19 July 2013.</ref> Greek parliament affirmed the [[Greek genocide|genocide of Greeks]] in Asia Minor as a whole (Pontian and Anatolian [[Ottoman Greeks]]), and designated 14 September a day of commemoration.<ref>Holocaust & Intolerance Museum of New Mexico. ''[http://www.nmholocaustmuseum.org/GenocideInHistory_StudyGuide.pdf The Greek Genocide].'' '''Genocide in History.''' June 2011. p. 27 (GIH_Greek_1). Retrieved: 19 July 2013.</ref>\n*20th century Notable Greek Orthodox modern writers include: Metr. [[John Zizioulas]] of Pergamon; Archimandrite Vasileios Gontikakis;{{#tag:ref|The Archimandrite Vasileios Gontikakis, who was abbot of [[Stavronikita monastery|Stavronikita]] for twenty years and since 1990 has been abbot of [[Iviron monastery|Iveron]], is generally recognized as the most representative spokesman of the monastic renewal on [[Mt. Athos]]. His books - ''Hymn of Entry, Abba Isaac the Syrian, The Parable of the Prodigal, Theological Commentary on the Iconography of the Monastery of Stavronikita'' - have been translated and reprinted many times. They are written in a theological style totally new in Greece, reflecting the immediacy of real experience. Gontikakis is the great witness to \"[[Philokalia]]n\" spirituality.<ref>[[Christos Yannaras]]. ''Orthodoxy and the West: Hellenic Self-Identity in the Modern Age.'' Transl. Peter Chamberas and Norman Russell. Brookline: Holy Cross Orthodox Press, 2006. p. 299.</ref>|group=note}} Prof. [[Christos Yannaras]]; Prof. Fr. [[John S. Romanides]] (\u20202001); Bp. [[Hierotheos (Vlachos)]] of Nafpaktos; Protopresbyter [[Nikolaos Loudovikos]]; Protopresbyter [[George Metallinos]]; Protopresbyter [[Theodore Zisis]];{{#tag:ref|See: {{in lang|el}} ''[[:el:\u03a0\u03c1\u03c9\u03c4\u03bf\u03c0\u03c1\u03b5\u03c3\u03b2\u03cd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u0398\u03b5\u03cc\u03b4\u03c9\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u0396\u03ae\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2|\u03a0\u03c1\u03c9\u03c4\u03bf\u03c0\u03c1\u03b5\u03c3\u03b2\u03cd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u0398\u03b5\u03cc\u03b4\u03c9\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u0396\u03ae\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2]].'' \u0392\u03b9\u03ba\u03b9\u03c0\u03b1\u03af\u03b4\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1. (Greek Wikipedia).|group=note}} Prof. Georgios Mantzaridis; and Panayiotis Nellas (\u20201986), among others.\n*2000\u20132001 Government of Greece orders '''removal of compulsory reference to religious affiliation on state identity cards''', despite widespread campaigns against this from the Church of Greece and the majority of the public.<ref name=GM/><ref>Patrick Quinn. ''\"Greek church demands referendum on religion on identity cards.\"'' Associated Press. 28 August 2001.</ref><ref>Elena Becatoros. ''Church escalates battle with government in ID showdown.'' '''The Associated Press (AP)'''. 14 June 2000.</ref><ref>''GREEK ORTHODOX CHURCH RALLIES CITIZENS TO FIGHT THE GOVERNMENT ON IDENTITY; CARD CHANGE.'' '''St. Louis Post-Dispatch (Missouri)'''. 15 June 2000.</ref>{{#tag:ref|The church took the unprecedented step of organizing the collection of signatures demanding that a referendum be held on the issue of the new identity cards and their mention of religion. The collection of signatures dragged on for several months, well into 2001. In the end, the church claimed to have collected over three million signatures.<ref name=GM/>|group=note}}\n*2001 Death of '''Elder Haralambos Dionysiatis''', teacher of [[Jesus Prayer|noetic prayer]];<ref>Monk Joseph Dionysiatis. ''Abbot Haralambos Dionysiatis the Teacher of Noetic Prayer.'' 1st Ed.. Athens 2004. 286 pages. {{ISBN|9789603515098}}</ref> on the first trip to Greece by a Pope since AD 710, [[Pope John Paul II]] of Rome apologizes to Orthodox Church for [[Fourth Crusade]];<ref>Richard Boudreaux. ''\"Pope Apologizes for Anti-Orthodox Past; Greece: John Paul begs forgiveness for Roman Catholics' history of sins against 'brothers.\"'' '''Los Angeles Times'''. 5 May 2001: News: p.A-1.</ref> a day earlier some 1,000 Orthodox conservatives took to the streets to denounce his visit;<ref>R. Jeffrey Smith and Sarah Delaney. ''Papal Trip Angers Greek Clergy. John Paul's Visit to Orthodox Stronghold First Since 1054.'' '''The Washington Post'''. 4 May 2001. Pg. A19.</ref> in March, Abp. [[Archbishop Christodoulos of Athens|Christodoulos (Paraskevaides) of Athens]] blessed the ''Hellenic Genocide Petition Effort'', which urged that the government not violate Law 2675/98 by deleting the term \"genocide\" when explaining the destruction of Hellenism in Asia Minor;<ref>Christodoulos, Archbishop of Athens and All Greece. ''[http://www.greece.org/main/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=528&Itemid=480 Archbishop Christodoulos Blesses the Hellenic Genocide Petition Effort].'' '''Hellenic Electronic Center'''. 22 March 2001.</ref> Abp. Christodoulos (Paraskevaides) of Athens visits the [[Russian Orthodox Church|Patriarchate of Moscow]], being also received by Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]];<ref>''[http://www.greekembassy.org/embassy/Content/en/Article.aspx?office=2&folder=324&article=8569 Christodoulos' Moscow visit].'' Hellenic Republic \u2013 Embassy of Greece (Athens News Agency). 8 May 2001.</ref><ref>''[http://www.mospat.ru/archive/en/ne105064.htm His Holiness Patriarch Alexy and His Beatitude Archbishop Christodoulos visits the memorial church on Poklonnaya Hill].'' Department for External Church Relations of the Russian Orthodox Church. 11.05.2001.</ref> '''pastoral agreement between the [[Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Coptic Orthodox Church]] and [[Greek Orthodox Patriarchate of Alexandria and all Africa]]''', agreeing to accept the [[Marriage in the Eastern Orthodox Church|sacrament of marriage]] which is conducted in either Church, as well as performing all other sacraments to that new family of Mixed Christian Marriage;<ref>''[https://orthodoxjointcommission.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/pastoral-agreement-of-2001-between-the-coptic-orthodox-and-greek-orthodox-patriarchates-of-alexandria.pdf Pastoral Agreement Between The Coptic Orthodox Church And The Greek Orthodox Patriarchate of Alexandria and all Africa.]'' ORTHODOX UNITY (ORTHODOX JOINT COMMISSION). Cairo, in 05/04/2001. Retrieved: 20 February 2018.</ref> death of distinguished scholar [[Dimitri Obolensky]], Russian-born historian who traced the influence of [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine civilisation]] in Eastern European identity.<ref>''Professor Sir Dimitri Obolensky Russian-born historian who traced the influence of Byzantine civilisation in Eastern European identity.'' '''The Daily Telegraph (London)'''. 7 January 2002. p. 25.</ref>\n[[File:Vladimir Putin 8 May 2001-3.jpg|left|thumb|Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]], Patriarch of Moscow and All Russia [[Alexy II of Moscow|Alexii II]], and head of the Greek Orthodox Church [[Archbishop Christodoulos of Athens]] and all Greece, at the [[Moscow Kremlin|Kremlin in Moscow]].]]\n\n*2002 The [[Holy Synod#The Greek Holy Synod|Holy Synod]] of the Church of Greece rejected a proposal to introduce [[Modern Greek]] into the [[Divine Liturgy]] (similar to what the [[Second Vatican Council]] did for the Roman Catholic Church by allowing the use of the [[vernacular]] for the [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]]), opting to keep [[Koine Greek]] as it was spoken 2,000 years ago and used in [[New Testament]] texts;<ref>''\"Greek Orthodox ban modern Greek in liturgy. (News in Brief: Greece).\"'' '''Catholic Insight.''' Nov. 2002: 27+.</ref> [[orthodoxwiki:Metropolis of Glyfada|Metropolis of Glyfada]] is established as a new [[Metropolis (religious jurisdiction)|metropolis]] separating from [[orthodoxwiki:Metropolis of New Smyrna|Metropolis of Nea Smyrni]];<ref>\u1f39\u03b5\u03c1\u03ac \u039c\u03b7\u03c4\u03c1\u03cc\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c2 \u0393\u03bb\u03c5\u03c6\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1\u03c2. ''[http://www.imglyfadas.gr/portal/gr/details.asp?cdPro={1EFCFC5E-B590-47E1-BE32-7FDFAB7DB5F1} \u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u039f\u03a1\u0399\u039a\u039f - 1. \u1f3d\u03b4\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 \u03c4\u1fc6\u03c2 \u1f39\u03b5\u03c1\u1fb6\u03c2 \u039c\u03b7\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b5\u03c9\u03c2].'' Retrieved: 2013-07-12.</ref> [[Ecumenical Patriarch Bartholomew I of Constantinople]] declared the monks of [[Esphigmenou Monastery|Esphigmenou Monastery (Athos)]] as being in [[Schism (religion)|schism]] with the [[Orthodox Church]];<ref>Costas Kantouris. ''Monks say they will wage spiritual war to prevent eviction from Mount Athos.'' '''Associated Press Worldstream'''. 16 January 2003.</ref> Patr. Bartholomew I (Archontonis) of Constantinople and Pope John Paul II co-sign [https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/speeches/2002/june/documents/hf_jp-ii_spe_20020610_venice-declaration_en.html Venice Declaration of Environmental Ethics].<ref>''[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/speeches/2002/june/documents/hf_jp-ii_spe_20020610_venice-declaration_en.html COMMON DECLARATION OF JOHN PAUL II AND THE ECUMENICAL PATRIARCH HIS HOLINESS BARTHOLOMEW I].'' The Holy See. 10 June 2002. Retrieved: 29 July 2014.</ref>\n*2003 Abp. Christodoulos (Paraskevaides) of Athens inaugurated the Office of the [http://www.regue.org/ Representation of the Church of Greece to the European Union] in Brussels;<ref>''[http://orthodoxeurope.org/page/14/25.aspx#4 Orthodox Church of Greece Opens New Offices of its Representation to the European Union].'' '''Europaica Bulletin''', No 25 (15 October 2003). Representation of the Russian Orthodox Church to the European Union (orthodoxeurope.org). Retrieved: 11 May 2013.</ref>{{#tag:ref|\"The emergence of an official office, the 'Representation of the Church of Greece' to the European Union, is a crucial landmark in the Europeanization process of the OCG, which reflects the aspiration of the latter to participate in the European process. It is a service abroad of the Holy Synod designed to represent the OCG in the EU.\"<ref>Vassiliki Karageorgiou (PhD Candidate, Dept. of Politics, University of Edinburgh). ''[http://www2.lse.ac.uk/europeanInstitute/research/hellenicObservatory/pdf/2nd_Symposium/Vassiliki_Karagerorgiou_paper.pdf The EU's impact on the Orthodox Church of Greece].'' Paper prepared for the 2nd LSE PhD Symposium on Modern Greece: Current Social Science Research on Greece. 10 June 2005, LSE. p. 14.</ref>|group=note}} Orthodox Churches in Europe commemorated the 550th anniversary of the [[Fall of Constantinople]] in May;{{#tag:ref|\"THE HORRIFIC event of the Fall itself falls into the domain of the unreachable judgments of the Wisdom of God, which transcend human understanding, represents the open wound of the Orthodox Christian conscience, but it is also a confirmation of the eternal truth, that the \"image of this world\" is passing, while at the same time a confirmation of the indestructibility of the One, Holy, Catholic and Apostolic Church, according to the promise of Christ. REMEMBERING, therefore, the [[Fall of Constantinople]], we venerate the wounds of the Crucified Lord and confirm ourselves in the power of His Resurrection, witnessing before all peoples Him as the Stone, which the builders rejected and reject, and He has become the \"Cornerstone, and this is marvelous in our eyes\". In that name we offer brotherly veneration to Your Beatitude and to all the participants in the convocation marking the 550th Anniversary of the Fall of Constantinople, greeting you with the joyous Paschal greeting: \"[[Paschal greeting|CHRIST IS RISEN!]]\"<ref>ELPENOR: Home of the Greek Word. ''[http://www.ellopos.net/elpenor/greek-texts/fathers/pavle-constantinople.asp?pg=3 Pavle of Serbia: 550 years since the fall of Constantinople: 29 May 1453\u20132003].'' Publ. Serbian Orthodox Church, Belgrade. 29 May 2003.</ref>|group=note}} the Greek Minister of Culture [[Evangelos Venizelos]] informs Europarliament session that the status of the monasteries on Holy Mount Athos and its way of life will remain unchanged, citing official recognition of this status fixed in Article 105 of the [[Constitution of Greece|Greek Constitution]] and also legally confirmed in the special Athens Treaty clause specifying conditions on which Greece joined the European Union;<ref>Spiridon Hatzaras (Press Councilor of the Greek Embassy in Moscow). ''[http://www.mospat.ru/archive/en/ne301223.htm Status of the Holy Mount Athos and its way of life will stay unchanged].'' Department for External Church Relations of the Russian Orthodox Church. (DECR). 31 January 2003.</ref><ref>Josep Maria Mallarach (Ed.). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=NXWxbvFEi8sC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false Protected Landscapes and Cultural Amb 'i.e. And'; Spiritual Values]''. Volume 2 of Values of Protected Landscapes and Seascapes. Kasparek Verlag, 2008. p. 52. {{ISBN|9783925064609}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|\"The Common Declaration on Mount Athos attached to the Treaty of entry of Greece to the EEC (1 January 1981) recognises the special status of Mount Athos as this is defined in article 105 of the Greek Constitution. Consequently, EU takes into consideration this status and particularly on matters of taxation exemption and rights of installation.\"<ref>Hellenic Republic Ministry of Interior, Public Administration and Decentralisation. ''[http://unpan1.un.org/intradoc/groups/public/documents/untc/unpan000205.pdf Structure and Operation of Local and Regional Democracy in Greece].'' Athens, 2000. p. 5.</ref>|group=note}} Abp. [[Archbishop Christodoulos of Athens|Christodoulos (Paraskevaides) of Athens]] has falling out with Ecumenical [[Ecumenical Patriarch Bartholomew I of Constantinople|Patriarch Bartholomew]] over who should have the final say in the appointment of bishops in northern Greece, but rift is mended three weeks later;<ref name=BART-CHRISTOD>''Orthodox church leaders agree to restore communion.'' '''Associated Press Worldstream'''. 20 May 2004.</ref>{{#tag:ref|The Greek church has since 1928 had administrative, but not titular, control over several dioceses in northern Greece \u2013 including Thessaloniki.<ref name=BART-CHRISTOD/>|group=note}} in February, the Holy Synod of the Greek Orthodox Church issued a statement opposing the threat of war in Iraq;<ref>''[http://www.mospat.ru/archive/en/ne302202.htm The Greek Orthodox Church opposes the war in Iraq].'' Department for External Church Relations of the Russian Orthodox Church. 4.03.2003.</ref> the Church of Greece sent more than 20 tons in humanitarian aid for the refugees of the war in Iraq to be distributed along the Jordanian-Iraqi border;<ref>''Church Of Greece Aids War Victims.'' '''Hellenic Times (New York)'''. Pg. 8, Vol. XXX No. 6 {{ISSN|1059-2121}}. 17 April 2003.</ref> the proposal to build a mosque outside Athens before the 2004 Olympics was blocked due to opposition from residents and Greece's Orthodox Church which disagreed with the location and plans for the funding for the multimillion-pound mosque to come from Saudi Arabia's King Fahd;<ref>''[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2003/sep/16/religion.uk Villagers try to block Athens mosque plan].'' '''The Guardian (UK)'''. 16 September 2003 02.27 BST.</ref><ref>Konstantinos Tsitselikis. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=FdqRdctzEXcC&source=gbs_navlinks_s Old and New Islam in Greece: From Historical Minorities to Immigrant Newcomers].'' Volume 5 of Studies in International Minority and Group Rights, {{ISSN|2210-2132}}. Martinus Nijhoff Publishers, 2012. pp. 266\u2013269.</ref> the 5th Academic Meeting between Judaism And Orthodox Christianity was held in Thessaloniki, Greece, on 27\u201329 May;<ref>''[http://www.jcrelations.net/Fifth+Academic+Meeting+between+Judaism+and+Orthodox+Christianity+in+Thessaloniki%2C+Greece.2747.0.html?L=3 Fifth Academic Meeting between Judaism and Orthodox Christianity in Thessaloniki, Greece].'' '''Jewish-Christian Relations'''. 2003-06-05.</ref> [[orthodoxwiki:Inter-Orthodox Consultation on the Draft Constitutiona