ligious Affairs|Greek Ministry for Education and Religion]];<ref>{{in lang|el}} ''' ''[http://www.greekbibles.org/index.php?id_product=21&controller=product&id_lang=1 \u0397 \u039a\u0391\u0399\u039d\u0397 \u0394\u0399\u0391\u0398\u0397\u039a\u0397: \u03a4\u03bf \u03c0\u03c1\u03c9\u03c4\u03cc\u03c4\u03c5\u03c0\u03bf \u03ba\u03b5\u03af\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03bf \u03bc\u03b5 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03ac\u03c6\u03c1\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7 \u03b4\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae].'' \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u0392\u03b9\u03b2\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u0395\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03af\u03b1, \u0391\u03b8\u03ae\u03bd\u03b1. {{ISBN|9789607847171}}'''</ref> [[Mystras]] is designated as a [[List of World Heritage Sites in Europe#Greece (17)|UNESCO World Heritage site]];<ref>''[https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/511 Archaeological Site of Mystras].'' \u00a9 UNESCO World Heritage Centre 1992\u20132012.</ref>\n*1990 '''Bilateral declarations of both [[Greece\u2013Israel relations|Greece and Israel]]''' are made on 21 May 1990 in which they normalized their diplomatic relations, essentially '''recognizing the special interest of the [[Greek Government]] in a [[Greek Orthodox]] presence in the [[Holy places#Christianity|Holy Places]]''', as well as its right to have a say in any future arrangements concerning the religious status quo and the rights and privileges of the [[Greek Orthodox Church of Jerusalem|Patriarchate of Jerusalem]];<ref>Sotiris Roussos. ''THE PATRIARCHATE OF JERUSALEM IN THE GREEK-PALESTINIAN-ISRAELI TRIANGLE: IS THERE A PLACE FOR IT?'' Athens, 1 March 2003. p. 8.</ref> the monasteries of [[Daphni Monastery|Daphni]] (Athens), [[Hosios Loukas]] (Beotia) and [[Nea Moni of Chios]], are designated as [[List of World Heritage Sites in Europe#Greece (17)|UNESCO World Heritage sites]];<ref>''[https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/537 Monasteries of Daphni, Hosios Loukas and Nea Moni of Chios].'' \u00a9 UNESCO World Heritage Centre 1992\u20132012.</ref> death of Fr. Athanasios Anthides, first Greek Orthodox Missionary to India, succeeded a year later by [[Hieromonk|priest-monk]] Fr. Ignatios Sennis, who came to [[Kolkata|Calcutta]] to continue the mission;<ref name=ORIANTHIDES/> the [[Mount Athos#The Friends of Mount Athos|Friends of Mount Athos]] society is formed, with Metr. [[Timothy Ware|Kallistos (Ware)]] of Diokleia as President,<ref>''[http://www.athosfriends.org/ Friends of Mount Athos Online].'' '''The Friends of Mount Athos'''. Retrieved: 24 July 2013.</ref> including [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]] (Duke of Edinburgh) and [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]] (The Prince of Wales) among its members.<ref>''[http://www.athosfriends.org/about/officiary/ The Officiary of the Friends of Mount Athos].'' '''The Friends of Mount Athos'''. Retrieved: 24 July 2013.</ref>\n*1991 Death of Elder [[Porphyrios Bairaktaris|Porphyrios (Bairaktaris) the Kapsokalivite]] (Evangelos (Bairaktaris)) 7 February;<ref>Kleitos I\u014dannid\u0113s, and Charles J. Simones. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=7FYnAAAACAAJ&dq=Porphyrios+testimonies+and+experiences&source=bl&ots=0TY8AXm_Ve&sig=zBcVw_NHmjcvIVfUfpQlXmqJlw8&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Jr9UUNy1EKrE0AH4-YGIBw&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA Elder Porphyrios testimonies and experiences].'' Holy Convent of the Transfiguration of the Savior, 1997. 367 pp. {{ISBN|9789608538238}}</ref><ref>''[http://www.orthodoxphotos.com/Orthodox_Elders/Greek/Fr._Porphyrios/ A Short Biography of Elder Porphyrios the Kapsokalivite].'' OrthodoxPhotos.com.</ref> '''[[orthodoxwiki:Kyriopascha|Kyriopascha]] occurs''';<ref group=\"note\" name=\"Kyriopascha\">From antiquity the Orthodox Church has celebrated with special liturgical joy the occurrence when [[Easter|Pascha]] falls on [[March 25 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)|25 March]] ([[Julian calendar|Old Style]]) - the [[Feast of the Annunciation]], calling it ''\"Kyriopascha,\"'' \"the Lord's Pascha\". It was precisely on the coincidence of the Feasts of the Annunciation and Pascha on 25 March 1821 (Old Style), that Greece challenged the Turkish Yoke. Kyriopascha has also manifested its miraculous Grace to our own generation by its most recent occurrence in 1991, the year of the demise of Communism in Russia, a demise which, furthermore, was finalized by a last, desperate gasp in the form of an abortive Communist coup thwarted on 6 August (Old Style)\u2013the Feast of the Transfiguration. The last Kyriopascha on the Julian calendar was in 1991; the next will be in 2075, 2086 and 2159. The last Kyriopascha on the Gregorian Calendar was in 1951, and the next will be in 2035, 2046 and 2103.</ref> '''[[Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of Italy]]''' is created;<ref>''[http://win.ortodossia.it/The%20Holy%20Orthodox%20Archdiocese%20of%20Italy%20ed%20Malta.htm The Holy Orthodox Archdiocese of Italy and Malta].'' Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of Italy. Retrieved: 29 July 2014.</ref> '''[[Syncretism|syncretistic]] synod of the [[Greek Orthodox Church of Antioch|Antiochian Patriarchate]]''' convened and presided over by Patriarch [[Ignatius IV of Antioch]], and attended by the heretical [[Monophysitism|Monophysite]] Jacobite Syrian Patriarch [[Ignatius Zakka I Iwas|Ignatius Zakka]], implements a series of measures aimed at achieving full union with the Monophysite [[Syriac Christianity|Syriac Churches]], declaring their patriarchates to be \"sister churches\"<ref name=1991-SYRIAC-ANTIOCH-STMT>''[http://sor.cua.edu/Ecumenism/19911112socrumorthstmt.html Statement of the Orthodox Church of Antioch on the Relations between the Eastern and Syrian Orthodox Churches].'' '''Syriac Orthodox Resources (SOR)'''. November 12, 1991. Retrieved: 20 August 2016.</ref> despite the [[Christology|Christological]] differences, and allowing joint prayer in the agreed statement.<ref name=1991-SYRIAC-ANTIOCH-STMT/><ref>''[http://www.gocamerica.org/history_canonicity_text_timeline.shtml Timeline of the Church of the Genuine Orthodox Christians of Russia and Greece and the Great Apostasy of Orthodoxy in the 20th Century].'' TWENTY-FOURTH EDITION. '''Dormition Skete''', Buena Vista, Colorado, U.S.A. MARCH 21, 2016.</ref><ref>''[http://genuineorthodoxchurch.com/A_Time_Line_of_the_20th_and_21st_Centuries.htm Genuine Orthodox Church of the 20th and 21st Centuries: A Time Line].'' '''Genuine Orthodox Church of Greece'''. Retrieved: 20 August 2016.</ref>{{#tag:ref|This action by the Patriarchate of Antioch was protested by the Sacred Community of Mount Athos, in a Letter to the Ecumenical Patriarch Concerning the Balamand Agreement, December 8, 1993, which was signed by all the Representatives and Presidents of the Twenty Sacred Monasteries of the Holy Mountain of Athos:\n:* \"...we cite the case of the Patriarchate of Antioch, which, without a Pan-Orthodox decision, has proceeded to ecclesiastical communion with the Non-Chalcedonians [Monophysites]. This was done despite the fact that a most serious issue has not yet been resolved. It is the latter's non-acceptance of the Ecumenical Councils after the Third and, in particular, the Fourth, the Council of Chalcedon, which in fact constitutes an immovable basis of Orthodoxy. Unfortunately, in this case, too, we have not seen a single protest by other Orthodox Churches.\"<ref name=ATHOS-DEC1993>''[http://orthodoxinfo.com/ecumenism/athos_bal.aspx Letter to the Ecumenical Patriarch Concerning the Balamand Agreement].'' '''Orthodox Christian Information Center'''. Retrieved: 20 August 2016. (From: ''Orthodox Life'', Vol. 44, No. 4, July\u2013August 1994, pp. 26-39.)</ref>|group=note}}\n\n{{multiple image\n| footer = Among the victims of the atrocities committed by the Turkish nationalist Army (1922\u201323) were hundreds of Christian clergy in Anatolia, such as metropolitan bishops (from left): [[Chrysostomos of Smyrna]] (lynched), [[Prokopios Lazaridis|Prokopios of Iconium]] (imprisoned and poisoned) [[Gregory Orologas|Gregory]] of Kydonies (executed), [[Ambrosios Pleianthidis|Ambrosios]] of Moschonisia (buried alive). These bishops were glorified by the Orthodox [[Church of Greece]] in 1992.\n| image1 = Chrysostomos of Smyrna.jpg | width1 = 100 | alt1 = Chrysostomos of Smyrna\n| image2 =| width2 = 106 | alt2 = Prokopios of Iconium\n| image3 = Gregory Orologas of Kydonies.jpg | width3 = 87 | alt3 = Gregory Orologas of Kynonies\n| image4 = Ambrosios of Moschonisia Asia Minor.jpg | width4 = 105 | alt4 = Ambrosios of Moschonisia, Asia Minor}}\n*1992 '''Synaxis of primates of Orthodox churches in Constantinople''';<ref name=GUARDIANHELENASMITH>Helena Smith. ''ORTHODOX LEADERS ACCUSE VATICAN OF STEALING THEIR CHRISTIAN FLOCK.'' '''The Guardian (London)'''. 17 March 1992. Pg. 4.</ref>{{#tag:ref|\"AN unprecedented summit of world Orthodox leaders has ended with a strong attack on the Vatican, harming chances of an early improvement in the deeply troubled relations between the two Christian Church groups. Closing their meeting in Istanbul, the 12 spiritual heads of Eastern Christianity said attempts by Roman Catholics to proselytise in eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union had inflicted a \"most severe wound on the dialogue between the Churches which will be difficult to heal\". The leaders said: \"Traditional Orthodox countries have been considered 'missionary territories' [by the Vatican] and proselytism is practised with all the methods that have been condemned and rejected for decades by all Christians\".\"<ref name=GUARDIANHELENASMITH/>|group=note}} Patr. [[Patriarch Diodoros of Jerusalem|Diodoros I of Jerusalem]] presented a list of '''[http://orthodoxinfo.com/ecumenism/diodoros.aspx firm declarations of Orthodox convictions]''' of the Patriarchate of Jerusalem, which was entered into the minutes of the assembly of Orthodox leaders at the Phanar on the Sunday of Orthodoxy;<ref>[http://orthodoxinfo.com/ecumenism/diodoros.aspx Firm Declarations of Patriarch Diodoros That Strengthen the Faith of Orthodox People]. Orthodox Christian Information Center. Retrieved: 29 July 2014.</ref><ref>Constantine Cavarnos. ''[http://ctosonline.org/ecumenism/QU.html The Question of Union].'' Etna, CA: The Center for Traditionalist Orthodox Studies, 1992 [1964].</ref> on 4 November 1992, the [[Holy Synod]] of the Church of Greece unanimously declared Bp. [[Chrysostomos of Smyrna]] (\u20201922) an Ethnomartyr and a [[Saint]] of the [[Orthodox Church]], to be jointly commemorated on the Sunday before the Feast of the [[Elevation of the Holy Cross]], together with four other Holy Hierarchs of [[Asia Minor]] including: Bp. [[Ambrosios Pleianthidis|Ambrosios Moschonision]], Bp. [[orthodoxwiki:Euthymios (Agritellis) of Zela|Euthymios (Agritellis) of Zela]] (\u20201921), Bp. [[Gregory (Orologas) of Kydonies|Gregorios of Kidonion]] (\u20201922), and Bp. [[Prokopios Lazaridis|Prokopios of Iconium]] (\u20201923);<ref>{{in lang|el}} ''[http://www.triglia.gr/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=26&Itemid=39+%CE%91%CE%B3%CE%B9%CE%BF%CF%82+%CE%A7%CF%81%CF%85%CF%83%CE%BF%CF%83%CF%84%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BF%CF%82+%CE%A3%CE%BC%CE%B7%CF%81%CE%BD%CE%B7%CF%82&ct=clnk \u0391\u03b3. \u03a7\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03cc\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a3\u03bc\u03cd\u03c1\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20110721083437/http://www.triglia.gr/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=26&Itemid=39+%CE%91%CE%B3%CE%B9%CE%BF%CF%82+%CE%A7%CF%81%CF%85%CF%83%CE%BF%CF%83%CF%84%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BF%CF%82+%CE%A3%CE%BC%CE%B7%CF%81%CE%BD%CE%B7%CF%82&ct=clnk |date=21 July 2011 }}.'' Municipality of [[Triglia]]. Retrieved: 7 September 2012.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Their ranking to the chorus of the Saints was formally announced in ''Encyclical 2556, of 5 July 1993, of the Holy Synod of the Church of Greece'' ({{in lang|el}} \u0395\u03b3\u03ba\u03cd\u03ba\u03bb\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 2556 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 5\u03b7\u03c2 \u0399\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 1993 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0399\u03b5\u03c1\u03ac\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c5\u03